## Gated paths (extra review independent of the spec's risk tier)
Any change touching these is held to extra review and may trip the security gate:
- `{{AUTH_PATHS}}` — authentication / identity / authorization
- `{{DATA_PATHS}}` — schema migrations, data access
- `{{PIPELINE_PATHS}}` — `.github/`, the hooks, this CLAUDE.md, branch protection
- `{{INFRA_PATHS}}` — `infra/` (IaC is HIGH risk every time)
- `{{PROMPT_PATHS}}` — prompts, model selection, tool definitions (see "Agentic work" below)

## Spec convention
One feature = one file `specs/NNNN-name.md` = one branch `spec/NNNN-name` = one squash-merged PR.
The spec is part of the diff so the reviewer sees intent and implementation in one view. The
seven parts: **Goal · Why · Scope in/out · Acceptance checks · Risk tier · Delegation plan
(what you may touch, what's gated) · Checking plan (which rungs).** Template: `spec-template.md`.

## Repo etiquette
- Branch `spec/NNNN-name`. You push **only to branches you create**, never to `{{DEFAULT_BRANCH}}`.
- You **cannot approve or merge your own work** — platform-enforced.
- Every agent commit is **co-authored** (provenance in history).
- Squash merge; conventional-commit title (`type: description`, imperative, under 72 chars).

---

## Metrics discipline (so the dashboard doesn't lie)
- **When a metric has no data, report "no data" — never a fabricated zero.** A zero reads as a
  measured result and steers the room wrong.
- **Never tracked, never reported:** velocity, story points, PR count, lines of code. Agents
  inflate all of them.

## Data boundary & secrets (non-negotiable)
- Secrets live in {{CLIENT}}'s Key Vault and GitHub secrets. **Never in code, never in this file,
  never in specs.** A key in a commit is the one unrecoverable mistake.
- The {{LLM_PROVIDER}} key is {{CLIENT}}-procured under their own agreement.
- Tag genuinely sensitive material out of agent context. See `docs/data-flow-brief.md`.

---

## Agentic work (applies when a spec's deliverable is LLM-powered)
"Tests pass" is not sufficient verification for probabilistic behavior.
- **Evals are acceptance criteria.** An agentic spec ships a **golden set** versioned next to the
  spec and a **threshold** (e.g. ">= {{EVAL_THRESHOLD}}% of the golden set"). CI runs evals like tests.
- **Prompts, model selections, and tool definitions are HIGH risk.** Any change runs the
  **eval-regression gate**; degradation blocks like a failing test. **No drive-by prompt edits.**
- **Observability is required:** tracing (what the agent saw, decided, called), token cost per
  task, failure-mode logging.
- Model output is **untrusted input**. No raw user input embedded in system prompts. Tool
  permissions enforced **server-side, not by prompt**.

